1
00:00:40,020 --> 00:00:42,614
<i>[Man Narrating]</i>
<i>Babe Ruth, Ty Cobb, Lou Gehrig...</i>

2
00:00:42,689 --> 00:00:45,419
<i>Hank Aaron, Mickey Mantle...</i>

3
00:00:45,492 --> 00:00:47,653
<i>Al Kaline, Carl Yastrzemski...</i>

4
00:00:47,728 --> 00:00:51,892
<i>Pete Rose, Barry Bonds,</i>
<i>Cal Ripken and a handful more...</i>

5
00:00:51,965 --> 00:00:53,933
<i>are all considered</i>
<i>to be the greatest hitters...</i>

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:56,696
<i>in baseball's celebrated history.</i>

7
00:00:56,770 --> 00:01:00,797
<i>But this list would not be complete</i>
<i>without one name in particular.</i>

8
00:01:00,874 --> 00:01:03,741
<i>Tommy “Santa” Santorelli.</i>

9
00:01:03,810 --> 00:01:07,109
<i>In the middle of his 19th</i>
<i>and recently announced final season...</i>

10
00:01:07,180 --> 00:01:10,149
<i>Tommy has been named</i>
<i>to 11 all-star teams...</i>

11
00:01:10,217 --> 00:01:13,584
<i>broken dozens of records,</i>
<i>and seems destined for Cooperstown.</i>

12
00:01:13,653 --> 00:01:18,113
<i>That is, if his ego</i>
<i>doesn't get in the way.</i>

13
00:01:18,191 --> 00:01:21,422
<i>From humble beginnings,</i>
<i>Tommy Santorelli and his mother, Sara...</i>

14
00:01:21,495 --> 00:01:24,589
<i>moved to Southern California</i>
<i>the summer Tommy turned 13.</i>

15
00:01:24,664 --> 00:01:27,098
<i>It was there that Tommy</i>
<i>began playing sandlot ball...</i>

16
00:01:27,167 --> 00:01:31,467
<i>and let's just say he's always</i>
<i>had a talent for the game.</i>

17
00:01:31,538 --> 00:01:34,837
<i>It was with that July 4, 1976 catch...</i>

18
00:01:34,908 --> 00:01:38,742
<i>that Tommy single-handedly</i>
<i>won the all-city championship.</i>

19
00:01:38,812 --> 00:01:41,576
<i>Unfortunately, shortly thereafter...</i>

20
00:01:41,648 --> 00:01:44,310
<i>Tommy's mother lost</i>
<i>a courageous battle with cancer...</i>

21
00:01:44,384 --> 00:01:46,409
<i>and a local benefactor sent him...</i>

22
00:01:46,486 --> 00:01:50,081
<i>to the legendary Baseball Academy</i>
<i>St. Agnus Preparatory School.</i>

23
00:01:50,157 --> 00:01:53,684
<i>It was there that he coined</i>
<i>his own nickname...”“Santa. “</i>

24
00:01:53,760 --> 00:01:59,255
<i>His explanation? Simple. It was a gift</i>
<i>for anyone to watch him play.</i>

25
00:01:59,332 --> 00:02:02,426
<i>The loss of his mother</i>
<i>affected him deeply, and some see this...</i>

26
00:02:02,502 --> 00:02:05,062
<i>as the reason for Tommy's</i>
<i>lack of loyalty to the list...</i>

27
00:02:05,138 --> 00:02:07,299
<i>of major league teams</i>
<i>he's been a part of.</i>

28
00:02:07,374 --> 00:02:09,842
<i>Finishing his career where it started...</i>

29
00:02:09,910 --> 00:02:11,969
<i>in his hometown of Los Angeles...</i>

30
00:02:12,045 --> 00:02:14,775
<i>Tommy signed a three-year,</i>
<i>multi-million-dollar deal...</i>

31
00:02:14,848 --> 00:02:17,612
<i>with the Dodgers.</i>

32
00:02:17,684 --> 00:02:19,982
<i>Though Tommy's numbers</i>
<i>have been strong...</i>

33
00:02:20,053 --> 00:02:24,717
<i>the Dodgers have suffered</i>
<i>their worst losing streak in years.</i>

34
00:02:24,791 --> 00:02:28,852
- [All Groan]
- <i>Famed Dodger manager</i>
<i>Benny Rodriguez explains:</i>

35
00:02:28,929 --> 00:02:32,023
<i>Problem is, guys like Tommy</i>
<i>don't play for the love of the game...</i>

36
00:02:32,098 --> 00:02:34,658
and that translates
to the rest of the guys.

37
00:02:34,734 --> 00:02:38,864
If the top earner don't care,
why should they?

38
00:02:38,939 --> 00:02:41,373
Now, these kids...

39
00:02:41,441 --> 00:02:43,534
They played because
they loved playing. That's it.

40
00:02:43,610 --> 00:02:46,511
No... No money, no agents.

41
00:02:46,580 --> 00:02:49,310
<i>[Chuckles]</i>
<i>No complaining.</i>

42
00:02:49,382 --> 00:02:51,509
Just the pure love of the game.

43
00:02:51,585 --> 00:02:55,316
[Sighs] But ballplayers like them
don't exist anymore.

44
00:02:55,388 --> 00:02:57,686
In fact, the old sandlot
doesn't even exist.

45
00:02:57,757 --> 00:03:00,692
But, yeah, they got it.

46
00:03:00,760 --> 00:03:03,661
Now, I've known Tommy
since he was a kid.

47
00:03:03,730 --> 00:03:06,824
We grew up
in the same town, and...

48
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:09,061
I don't know, maybe it's
'cause I'm older than him.

49
00:03:09,135 --> 00:03:12,036
But, uh, the sad thing is...

50
00:03:12,105 --> 00:03:14,938
I could always tell...
he never got it.

51
00:03:16,076 --> 00:03:18,169
What do I know?

52
00:03:18,245 --> 00:03:21,408
I'm just an old, washed-up
manager now anyhow.

53
00:03:21,481 --> 00:03:23,574
Let's get some dirt
on those uniforms, huh?

54
00:03:26,286 --> 00:03:29,084
<i>[Woman] So what do you think</i>
<i>went wrong today, Santa?</i>

55
00:03:29,155 --> 00:03:31,521
What are you askin' me for?
I went three for four.

56
00:03:31,591 --> 00:03:34,560
- Homered in the sixth,
in case you didn't see that.
- Yeah, but you lost.

57
00:03:34,628 --> 00:03:38,029
- No, sweetie. They lost.
- Did you just call me sweetie?

58
00:03:38,098 --> 00:03:40,089
Listen, I'm just trying
to be friendly, sweetie.

59
00:03:40,166 --> 00:03:44,068
Look. If these guys want to play
like a bunch of losers...

60
00:03:44,137 --> 00:03:46,435
there's nothing I can do
to stop 'em, okay?

61
00:03:46,506 --> 00:03:49,373
So, Tommy, with this being
your last season...

62
00:03:49,442 --> 00:03:51,774
you must be looking back
on your career a little bit.

63
00:03:51,845 --> 00:03:54,746
- Some say you're getting out
before the hammer falls.
- What?

64
00:03:54,814 --> 00:03:56,873
Any regrets?

65
00:03:56,950 --> 00:03:59,111
- Nope. None.
- Really?

66
00:03:59,185 --> 00:04:02,154
What about that tell-all book
written by your ex-fiancée, Judy Kroll...

67
00:04:02,222 --> 00:04:04,383
Sweetie?

68
00:04:04,457 --> 00:04:07,187
Tommy, come on.
What do you have to...

69
00:04:18,872 --> 00:04:21,636
Oh, it's a great day for baseball.

70
00:04:21,708 --> 00:04:25,303
<i>Yeah, and one of the last.</i>

71
00:04:25,378 --> 00:04:28,108
And I'll tell you what, boys.
When Santa's gone, party's over.

72
00:04:28,181 --> 00:04:30,672
You better cherish these days
while they're here.

73
00:04:30,750 --> 00:04:33,241
<i>He's in a talkative mood today.</i>

74
00:04:33,320 --> 00:04:35,083
Yeah. Probably 'cause
he's not under oath.

75
00:04:35,155 --> 00:04:37,123
Yo, 26, what gives?

76
00:04:37,190 --> 00:04:41,183
Uh, it's for the July 4
fireworks next week.

77
00:04:41,261 --> 00:04:43,855
That's next week.
What are they doin' in my yard today?

78
00:04:43,930 --> 00:04:48,094
I don't know.
That's just what I was told.

79
00:04:48,168 --> 00:04:50,295
You know, I've been comin' here
early for three years...

80
00:04:50,370 --> 00:04:53,134
so this diva can have B.P.
All to himself...

81
00:04:53,206 --> 00:04:56,004
- and he doesn't even know my name.
- Consider yourself lucky.

82
00:04:56,076 --> 00:04:58,271
At least you're on
a first-number basis with him.

83
00:04:58,345 --> 00:05:01,678
- Right.
- Yeah, they wanna see some fireworks?

84
00:05:02,849 --> 00:05:05,682
I'll show 'em some fireworks.

85
00:05:07,220 --> 00:05:10,018
Been workin' on that new pitch
we talked about?

86
00:05:10,090 --> 00:05:12,456
What new pitch?

87
00:05:12,525 --> 00:05:14,584
It's called a strike.

88
00:05:24,137 --> 00:05:26,970
And Santa takes that
to the North Pole.

89
00:05:36,816 --> 00:05:39,250
All right.

90
00:05:39,319 --> 00:05:42,254
So on the big night,
when I say "now"...

91
00:05:42,322 --> 00:05:45,587
I want you to light it up
right here, okay?

92
00:05:45,659 --> 00:05:47,684
Hey, Lou.

93
00:05:47,761 --> 00:05:50,059
- You understand me, right?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah, Bud.

94
00:05:50,130 --> 00:05:52,257
- I'm just watching out for incoming.
- Okay.

95
00:05:52,332 --> 00:05:55,893
You got a problem
with your breakin' stuff, kid.

96
00:05:57,837 --> 00:06:00,101
- Yeah? What's that?
- It don't break.

97
00:06:00,173 --> 00:06:03,836
- Excuse me?
- You're excused. Bring it.

98
00:06:04,911 --> 00:06:06,173
<i>You understand me, right?</i>

99
00:06:06,246 --> 00:06:08,771
On the big night, when I say "now"...

100
00:06:08,848 --> 00:06:11,578
- I want you to light it up. Okay?
- What, now?

101
00:06:11,651 --> 00:06:12,743
- Now.
- Now?

102
00:06:12,819 --> 00:06:14,252
- When I say "now," Lou.
- Now?

103
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:16,220
Lou, your head's like cement.
Now is now.

104
00:06:16,289 --> 00:06:17,847
- What do you mean, now?
- Now.

105
00:06:17,924 --> 00:06:19,255
Okay, now. Whoo!

106
00:06:19,325 --> 00:06:22,920
Lou! Not "now," now.
Pull it out.

107
00:06:24,931 --> 00:06:27,297
- <i>Pull it out!</i>
- What do you mean, pull it out?
You said light it.

108
00:06:27,367 --> 00:06:29,426
- Run!
- [Screams]

109
00:06:55,862 --> 00:06:57,887
<i>[Boy]</i>
<i>How far did he skid?</i>

110
00:06:57,964 --> 00:07:00,159
<i>[Boy #2]</i>
<i>Pace it off, Q.</i>

111
00:07:00,233 --> 00:07:02,827
Four, five, six, seven, eight...

112
00:07:02,902 --> 00:07:04,927
he looks bad.

113
00:07:08,174 --> 00:07:12,304
- We should do something.
- Yeah, kick him. See if he's fakin' it.

114
00:07:12,378 --> 00:07:17,145
- Kick him? What, are you nuts?
- "Nuts"? Good idea.

115
00:07:17,217 --> 00:07:19,742
Kick in the family jewels,
excellent fake breaker.

116
00:07:19,819 --> 00:07:23,346
- <i>[Boy #2] That should wake him up.</i>
- Bad idea on many levels.

117
00:07:23,423 --> 00:07:25,653
<i>As a medical procedure,</i>
<i>I think kicking...</i>

118
00:07:25,725 --> 00:07:28,353
is way down on the list
of any prescribed remedies.

119
00:07:28,428 --> 00:07:31,022
- Got any better ideas, Q?
- Slap in the face?

120
00:07:31,097 --> 00:07:32,621
Bucket of water.
That always works.

121
00:07:32,699 --> 00:07:34,860
My mom says you should
always wake someone gently.

122
00:07:34,934 --> 00:07:38,426
- Gently.
- How about seeking medical attention, doofus?

123
00:07:39,873 --> 00:07:41,932
The average ambulance
takes four minutes...

124
00:07:42,008 --> 00:07:44,169
to respond to the scene
of an accident.

125
00:07:44,244 --> 00:07:46,872
Kick in the family jewels,
lot faster.

126
00:07:46,946 --> 00:07:49,642
- We're gonna get this guy help.
- Why are you in charge?

127
00:07:49,716 --> 00:07:51,547
- Yeah, why are you in charge?
- Since when?

128
00:07:51,618 --> 00:07:53,677
- I'm the tallest.
- What's that got to do with anything?

129
00:07:53,753 --> 00:07:55,778
I am the smartest.

130
00:07:55,855 --> 00:07:58,790
I think you mean shortest.
I'm the biggest.

131
00:07:58,858 --> 00:08:02,521
- I think you mean fattest.
- Fattest.

132
00:08:02,595 --> 00:08:04,790
- I say we go with the kick.
- I'm the captain.

133
00:08:04,864 --> 00:08:07,162
- <i>[Boys] What?</i>
- Who made you captain, D. P?

134
00:08:07,233 --> 00:08:09,064
The catcher is always the captain.

135
00:08:09,135 --> 00:08:12,969
- You're not the captain. What about pitcher?
- [Chattering]

136
00:08:13,039 --> 00:08:15,633
- Guys, look. Guys. He's waking up.
- [Groaning]

137
00:08:15,708 --> 00:08:17,801
We could still kick him
before it's too late.

138
00:08:17,877 --> 00:08:20,368
<i>[Boy #2] Ask him a question</i>
<i>that everyone knows.</i>

139
00:08:20,446 --> 00:08:22,505
- See if he's okay.
- Good idea.

140
00:08:22,582 --> 00:08:24,641
Who's the greatest
baseball player of all time?

141
00:08:24,717 --> 00:08:27,185
- I am.
- [All] What?

142
00:08:27,253 --> 00:08:29,244
- <i>[Boy] Who are you?</i>
- Tommy Santorelli.

143
00:08:29,322 --> 00:08:32,257
Well, I don't care if you're Steve Garvey.
The answer is Babe Ruth.

144
00:08:32,325 --> 00:08:35,556
- Hello! The Sultan of Swat.
- The King of Crash.

145
00:08:35,628 --> 00:08:37,357
- The Colossus of Clout.
- The home Run King.

146
00:08:37,430 --> 00:08:40,160
- The Babe.
- [Together] The Great Bambino.

147
00:08:40,233 --> 00:08:43,031
No. It's Santa.

148
00:08:43,102 --> 00:08:45,400
- Santa?
- As in Claus?

149
00:08:45,471 --> 00:08:48,497
- [Groans]
- Can I kick him now?

150
00:08:48,575 --> 00:08:51,169
- Go ahead.
- <i>[Man] Back up, kids!</i>

151
00:08:51,244 --> 00:08:53,303
Clear out!

152
00:08:54,814 --> 00:08:56,907
[Panting]

153
00:08:56,983 --> 00:08:59,008
I'm trained for situations like this.

154
00:08:59,085 --> 00:09:01,178
Now, who started it?

155
00:09:14,334 --> 00:09:17,531
Stand back, boys.
I'm goin' in.

156
00:09:17,604 --> 00:09:19,868
[All Groaning]

157
00:09:25,778 --> 00:09:28,542
[Screaming]

158
00:09:29,716 --> 00:09:32,412
Hey! What's goin' on here?

159
00:09:32,485 --> 00:09:34,612
All right, kids, give him some air.
What happened?

160
00:09:34,687 --> 00:09:36,587
<i>[Boy]</i>
<i>He took a fly ball to the forehead.</i>

161
00:09:36,656 --> 00:09:39,386
- Sorry, Uncle Chops.
- <i>Would have been a triple too...</i>

162
00:09:39,459 --> 00:09:41,450
if he hadn't screwed it up.

163
00:09:41,527 --> 00:09:43,586
- In your dreams, fat ass.
- Hey, hey, hey, hey.

164
00:09:43,663 --> 00:09:45,790
Are we gonna have
a situation here?

165
00:09:45,865 --> 00:09:48,129
'Cause we don't want
a situation, do we? Huh?

166
00:09:48,201 --> 00:09:51,466
- [Boys] No.
- Good. What's your name, kid?

167
00:09:51,537 --> 00:09:54,097
Who you calling kid, tubs?

168
00:09:54,173 --> 00:09:57,233
Is that any way to talk
to an officer of the law?

169
00:09:57,310 --> 00:09:59,301
- Where's my P.D. A?
- Your what?

170
00:09:59,379 --> 00:10:02,109
- My blackberry?
- Hey, that's mine.

171
00:10:02,181 --> 00:10:04,274
And it's not blackberry.
It's strawberry-banana.

172
00:10:04,350 --> 00:10:06,818
- Are you serious? I love strawberry.
- Hey!

173
00:10:06,886 --> 00:10:09,116
He's that new kid
who just moved onto Glenview Road.

174
00:10:09,188 --> 00:10:11,952
<i>What are you talking about?</i>
<i>I live in Beverly Hills.</i>

175
00:10:12,025 --> 00:10:14,084
And what's up with this "kid" crap?

176
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:17,527
Which one of you jacked my phone?
I gotta call my agent.

177
00:10:17,597 --> 00:10:19,531
Don't even think about autographs.

178
00:10:19,599 --> 00:10:21,829
<i>[Boy] Why would we want</i>
<i>your autograph, loser?</i>

179
00:10:25,872 --> 00:10:28,170
1976.

180
00:10:28,241 --> 00:10:31,039
Bicentennial?

181
00:10:37,450 --> 00:10:39,680
What's goin' on?

182
00:10:41,955 --> 00:10:44,856
<i>Yeah. We got a situation.</i>

183
00:10:47,961 --> 00:10:52,728
- % % [Woman Singing Lullaby]
- [Moans]

184
00:10:52,799 --> 00:10:54,994
% % [humming]

185
00:10:55,068 --> 00:10:57,434
Where am I?

186
00:10:58,571 --> 00:11:01,005
You're home, sweetheart.

187
00:11:01,074 --> 00:11:03,668
No, I can't be.
I must be dreaming.

188
00:11:03,743 --> 00:11:07,076
Just relax.
You'll feel better in the morning.

189
00:11:10,316 --> 00:11:13,012
Mom.

190
00:11:13,086 --> 00:11:15,816
- It's really good to see you again.
- <i>[Chuckles]</i>

191
00:11:15,888 --> 00:11:19,085
- Honey.
- I've missed you so much.

192
00:11:19,158 --> 00:11:23,322
Oh, honey. I'm right here.

193
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:30,098
% % [humming]

194
00:11:33,239 --> 00:11:36,231
- I like this dream.
- Shh.

195
00:11:46,586 --> 00:11:48,850
<i>[Tommy Screams]</i>

196
00:11:55,962 --> 00:11:59,693
- Well, hello there, sleepyhead.
- Wh-Where am I?

197
00:11:59,766 --> 00:12:01,791
You're home, sweetheart.

198
00:12:01,868 --> 00:12:04,860
No, no, no.
Something's very wrong.

199
00:12:06,472 --> 00:12:09,737
Mom? Am I dead?

200
00:12:09,809 --> 00:12:12,277
Why would you ask
such a silly thing?

201
00:12:12,345 --> 00:12:15,280
Because I'm wearing my Speed Racer P.J.'s
that I haven't seen in 30 years.

202
00:12:15,348 --> 00:12:17,475
Fine. I got a little backed up
on the laundry.

203
00:12:17,550 --> 00:12:20,383
<i>There's still a lot</i>
<i>of unpacking to do.</i>

204
00:12:20,453 --> 00:12:23,320
Don't worry, your Batman and Robin
ones haven't run off.

205
00:12:23,389 --> 00:12:27,917
- Mom, do you know how old I am?
- Twelve, almost 13.

206
00:12:27,994 --> 00:12:32,124
No. I'm 41 years old.
I live in Beverly hills.

207
00:12:32,198 --> 00:12:35,964
<i>I've got a smokin'-hot girlfriend</i>
<i>who's got her own reality show.</i>

208
00:12:36,035 --> 00:12:38,094
I play center field for the Dodgers.

209
00:12:38,171 --> 00:12:40,969
<i>And somehow I'm back here.</i>

210
00:12:41,040 --> 00:12:44,134
And you're here.
And the pancakes smell so real.

211
00:12:44,210 --> 00:12:46,770
And I think I'm gonna throw up.

212
00:12:46,846 --> 00:12:49,508
All right, all right. Take it easy.
I thought you loved pancakes.

213
00:12:49,582 --> 00:12:53,416
- I'll make you some eggs.
- No eggs. I do protein shakes.

214
00:12:53,486 --> 00:12:57,946
- Ginseng, spirulina.
- Maybe you have a concussion
and I let you sleep too long.

215
00:12:58,024 --> 00:13:00,515
I'm gonna call the doctor right now.

216
00:13:00,593 --> 00:13:02,754
Mom, put down the phone.

217
00:13:02,829 --> 00:13:04,854
I don't think I have a concussion.

218
00:13:04,931 --> 00:13:06,922
I just think I'm dead.

219
00:13:10,369 --> 00:13:12,701
[Chuckling]

220
00:13:12,772 --> 00:13:15,673
I bet this'll bring you back to life.

221
00:13:16,776 --> 00:13:19,040
Give me a break.

222
00:13:19,112 --> 00:13:21,808
Has everyone gone nuts?

223
00:13:21,881 --> 00:13:25,783
<i>Okay, Tommy, why don't you</i>
<i>tell me what's wrong?</i>

224
00:13:25,852 --> 00:13:28,719
Come on, Doc. Isn't it your job
to tell me what's wrong?

225
00:13:28,788 --> 00:13:31,450
<i>All right.</i>
<i>Uh, how's your memory?</i>

226
00:13:31,524 --> 00:13:35,016
Well, I remember some things
like they were real.

227
00:13:35,094 --> 00:13:37,995
Like my mom and the house...

228
00:13:38,064 --> 00:13:40,498
and the kids from the sandlot.

229
00:13:40,566 --> 00:13:42,625
But other things,
they're kind of foggy.

230
00:13:42,702 --> 00:13:47,833
- Like I'm watching TiVo.
- TiVo? You mean TV? Uh, television?

231
00:13:47,907 --> 00:13:50,842
No, TiVo. Pausing real time,
zapping commercials.

232
00:13:50,910 --> 00:13:54,004
Unless I'm in them.

233
00:13:54,080 --> 00:13:57,208
Why don't you wait outside a minute
while I talk to your mom, okay?

234
00:13:57,283 --> 00:14:00,184
I'd actually prefer to stay, Doc.

235
00:14:00,253 --> 00:14:04,053
My trainers back at Dodger Stadium
give me the skinny all the time.

236
00:14:04,123 --> 00:14:06,387
That's what I mean. I don't know
half the things he's talking about.

237
00:14:06,459 --> 00:14:10,828
Well, his... Your retinas appear to be fine,
and the heart rate is normal.

238
00:14:10,897 --> 00:14:13,365
Other than a little bump
on your noggin, I think... [Chuckles]

239
00:14:13,432 --> 00:14:15,423
Well, he's fine.

240
00:14:15,501 --> 00:14:17,992
<i>[Tommy]</i>
<i>“Fine”? You think I'm fine?</i>

241
00:14:19,572 --> 00:14:21,665
Look at me.
Look at this haircut.

242
00:14:21,741 --> 00:14:23,766
Look at these weak little biceps.

243
00:14:23,843 --> 00:14:27,904
How can you call any of this fine?
Let's go, Mom.

244
00:14:27,980 --> 00:14:30,744
<i>This guy's a quack.</i>

245
00:14:30,816 --> 00:14:34,377
<i>Tommy, you apologize this instant.</i>

246
00:14:34,453 --> 00:14:36,444
No, no. That's okay.

247
00:14:36,522 --> 00:14:40,049
Actually, Tommy, I would like to have
another word with your mother though.

248
00:14:40,126 --> 00:14:43,425
- [Whispering] In private.
- Whatever.

249
00:14:43,496 --> 00:14:48,433
- <i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>
- Sara, I think Tommy's
suffering from some sort...

250
00:14:48,501 --> 00:14:52,232
<i>of emotional stress,</i>
<i>but he'll be fine.</i>

251
00:14:52,305 --> 00:14:55,297
You are the one that
I am concerned about.

252
00:14:55,374 --> 00:14:58,366
Me? I'm well, thank you.

253
00:15:01,447 --> 00:15:03,642
I guess I'm strong enough
for the chemo again.

254
00:15:03,716 --> 00:15:05,809
Mmm. Then maybe we should
pick up on the treatments...

255
00:15:05,885 --> 00:15:07,944
where you left off before the move.

256
00:15:08,020 --> 00:15:10,454
That'd be fine, Doctor.

257
00:15:10,523 --> 00:15:13,822
Now, if he starts acting up again...

258
00:15:13,893 --> 00:15:16,418
I'd show him some pictures
of family and friends...

259
00:15:16,495 --> 00:15:20,431
just to bring him back
to reality, as it were.

260
00:15:20,499 --> 00:15:23,093
Maybe that's what he's fighting.

261
00:15:23,169 --> 00:15:25,160
Reality.

262
00:15:26,305 --> 00:15:28,773
That was surreal.

263
00:15:28,841 --> 00:15:31,776
I don't know about you, Mom,
but I could sure use a drink.

264
00:15:31,844 --> 00:15:34,472
We could go get a soda.

265
00:15:36,649 --> 00:15:38,810
And this is your Uncle Henry.

266
00:15:40,686 --> 00:15:44,918
Uncle Henry. You remember
your Uncle Henry, don't you, sweetheart?

267
00:15:44,991 --> 00:15:47,960
Mmm, sure.
I remember Uncle Henry.

268
00:15:48,027 --> 00:15:50,621
Cheap son of a...
Who is this again?

269
00:15:50,696 --> 00:15:55,633
That's you.
And that's you at the lake.

270
00:15:55,701 --> 00:15:58,499
Oh. And there's you at Big Bear.

271
00:15:58,571 --> 00:16:01,438
And this is that day
last summer, you remember...

272
00:16:01,507 --> 00:16:03,941
when we went to that music festival
with your Cousin Jimmy?

273
00:16:04,010 --> 00:16:06,877
<i>Oh, right. Shame what happened</i>
<i>to him though.</i>

274
00:16:06,946 --> 00:16:10,006
What happened to him?
Did Margie call with some bad news?

275
00:16:10,082 --> 00:16:13,677
No. When Jimmy's band
broke up in the early '90s...

276
00:16:13,753 --> 00:16:16,881
he got himself a job
at home Depot in Calabasas.

277
00:16:16,956 --> 00:16:19,948
What's home Depot?

278
00:16:20,026 --> 00:16:22,460
Last I heard, he was
assistant manager in hardware.

279
00:16:22,528 --> 00:16:26,487
[Chuckles] Divorced,
up to his neck in alimony payments.

280
00:16:29,769 --> 00:16:32,738
- What?
- Little Jimmy’s in the fourth grade...

281
00:16:32,805 --> 00:16:36,002
and got all straight A's
this past year, Tommy.

282
00:16:39,145 --> 00:16:40,908
- Who's this again?
- <i>[Doorbell Rings]</i>

283
00:16:40,980 --> 00:16:43,380
- <i>[Kids Chattering]</i>
- I'll get that.

284
00:16:43,449 --> 00:16:45,508
- Guys, stop pushing.
- What's your problem?

285
00:16:45,584 --> 00:16:47,643
- Shut up.
- Guys, guys.

286
00:16:47,720 --> 00:16:50,154
Tommy, some boys
are here for you.

287
00:16:50,222 --> 00:16:53,055
- Get your hand off me.
- Good job.

288
00:16:53,125 --> 00:16:55,423
Shut up.

289
00:16:55,494 --> 00:16:59,396
- Hey, I'm D.P. This is Wings...
- Timber and Two Ton.

290
00:16:59,465 --> 00:17:02,434
<i>Yeah, I remember you guys.</i>
<i>It's all comin' back to me.</i>

291
00:17:02,501 --> 00:17:06,995
- Like it was yesterday.
- It was yesterday.

292
00:17:07,073 --> 00:17:10,270
Anyway, we just wanted
to see how you were feeling.

293
00:17:10,343 --> 00:17:14,336
<i>Yeah. Lucky it wasn't your eyeball.</i>

294
00:17:14,413 --> 00:17:16,347
<i>[Slurps, Pops]</i>

295
00:17:16,415 --> 00:17:19,714
Well, I'm fine now. Thanks for
stopping by, kids. See ya around.

296
00:17:19,785 --> 00:17:22,549
What's with this
constant "kid" crap?

297
00:17:22,621 --> 00:17:25,920
I'm really glad you're not
gonna be playing on our team.

298
00:17:25,991 --> 00:17:28,619
- What team?
- Our team. We play on the sandlot.

299
00:17:28,694 --> 00:17:32,460
- [Whispering] The sandlot.
- <i>[Wings] Yeah, sandlot.</i>

300
00:17:32,531 --> 00:17:36,023
- Needs another player.
- <i>And only because the best</i>
<i>ballplayer in the history...</i>

301
00:17:36,102 --> 00:17:39,765
of sandlot is back,
puttin' on a clinic.

302
00:17:39,839 --> 00:17:42,967
Who said anything about me
putting on a clinic?

303
00:17:43,042 --> 00:17:45,738
- You?
- I'm talkin' about Benny.

304
00:17:45,811 --> 00:17:47,711
- The Jet.
- Rodriguez.

305
00:17:47,780 --> 00:17:50,078
- [Chucking] That bum?
- <i>“Bum”?</i>

306
00:17:50,149 --> 00:17:53,277
He's got the best batting average
on the Dodgers this year.

307
00:17:54,653 --> 00:17:58,316
Wait. He's here too?

308
00:17:58,391 --> 00:18:00,382
- Benny's amazing, man.
- The best.

309
00:18:00,459 --> 00:18:04,486
Please. Benny only got as far
as he did because he can run.

310
00:18:04,563 --> 00:18:06,656
Then his knee tanked him.
He retired and became a coach.

311
00:18:06,732 --> 00:18:09,098
- What's he talking about?
- <i>[Sara] You should go with them, honey.</i>

312
00:18:09,168 --> 00:18:11,159
- <i>Fresh air'll do you some good.</i>
- But, Mom...

313
00:18:11,237 --> 00:18:13,899
<i>No buts. Get out. I'm serious.</i>

314
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:17,167
Let me get my mitt.

315
00:18:19,044 --> 00:18:22,104
- [Whispering] Guy's nuts.
- [Indistinct]

316
00:18:38,864 --> 00:18:41,264
[Sniffs]

317
00:18:42,501 --> 00:18:45,493
<i>% % [Folk-Rock]</i>

318
00:18:55,548 --> 00:18:57,982
<i>% % [Man Singing]</i>

319
00:18:58,050 --> 00:19:01,850
<i>% % [Continues]</i>

320
00:19:34,220 --> 00:19:36,313
<i>% % [Ends]</i>

321
00:19:36,388 --> 00:19:38,652
All right, so we're gonna do
some hitting, some fielding...

322
00:19:38,724 --> 00:19:40,715
and you're gonna play outfield.

323
00:19:40,793 --> 00:19:42,818
<i>D.P., behind the plate, as usual.</i>

324
00:19:42,895 --> 00:19:44,886
<i>[Wings]</i>
<i>We've got everybody here. Let's play.</i>

325
00:19:44,964 --> 00:19:46,659
<i>I want you three to play outfield.</i>

326
00:19:46,732 --> 00:19:49,223
<i>[Boy]</i>
<i>We've got this new kid today.</i>

327
00:19:49,301 --> 00:19:52,702
- <i>We're gonna have four outfielders then.</i>
- <i>That makes sense.</i>

328
00:19:52,771 --> 00:19:55,331
- <i>Let's play some ball.</i>
- <i>All right, fellas, let's go.</i>

329
00:19:55,407 --> 00:19:58,433
<i>I want you to focus. When I start talking,</i>
<i>I want you listening, okay?</i>

330
00:19:58,511 --> 00:20:00,911
<i>All right, let's go.</i>

331
00:20:00,980 --> 00:20:03,073
[Chattering, Whooping]

332
00:20:03,148 --> 00:20:07,084
- Hey, Benny, over here.
- You might wanna get a little further out there.

333
00:20:07,152 --> 00:20:09,586
- <i>[Boy] Out there, Two Ton.</i>
- Here we go, fellas.

334
00:20:09,655 --> 00:20:11,680
Hey, Benny.
It's pretty weird, right?

335
00:20:11,757 --> 00:20:14,248
I mean, it's like
<i>The Twilight Zone</i> or something.

336
00:20:14,326 --> 00:20:16,726
Maybe you could tell me
how we, uh, got...

337
00:20:16,795 --> 00:20:18,820
here.

338
00:20:20,266 --> 00:20:22,791
You asking me how I got here?

339
00:20:22,868 --> 00:20:24,927
Same way these kids
are gonna get there.

340
00:20:25,004 --> 00:20:28,531
- 'Cause they love to play ball.
That's the key, kid.
- You look so...

341
00:20:28,607 --> 00:20:30,598
- So...
- Yeah?

342
00:20:30,676 --> 00:20:34,237
- Well, young.
- Really?

343
00:20:34,313 --> 00:20:37,077
Maybe I should be lookin' in the same
mirror you're lookin' in, kid.

344
00:20:37,149 --> 00:20:39,447
<i>No, I wouldn't really</i>
<i>recommend that.</i>

345
00:20:39,518 --> 00:20:41,645
Come on, hotshot.
Let's see what you got.

346
00:20:41,720 --> 00:20:44,314
You know what?
I think I'm just gonna watch.

347
00:20:44,390 --> 00:20:47,257
- Okay.
- Some all-star.

348
00:20:47,326 --> 00:20:49,317
"All-star"? Ha.

349
00:20:49,395 --> 00:20:52,762
As in, "I'll start later."
Just full of it.

350
00:20:55,568 --> 00:20:58,969
I'll tell you, try to do a weirdo a favor,
and it just gets "weirdo-er."

351
00:20:59,038 --> 00:21:01,563
- <i>Yeah, really.</i>
- Get ready, fellas. Here it comes.

352
00:21:01,640 --> 00:21:03,801
- <i>Let's go.</i>
- <i>Get it!</i>

353
00:21:03,876 --> 00:21:05,901
- <i>Come on. That's it.</i>
- I've got it.

354
00:21:05,978 --> 00:21:09,106
<i>Nice. Now throw it back home.</i>

355
00:21:09,181 --> 00:21:11,581
<i>Oh, nice throw.</i>

356
00:21:13,519 --> 00:21:16,044
<i>Yeah, nice catch.</i>

357
00:21:23,696 --> 00:21:25,789
You new to town?

358
00:21:25,864 --> 00:21:28,697
- Not really.
- I'm Squints Palledorous.

359
00:21:28,767 --> 00:21:32,703
- Baseball commissioner, right?
- Yeah, that's right.

360
00:21:32,771 --> 00:21:34,363
<i>Go, Wings! Go, Wings!</i>

361
00:21:34,440 --> 00:21:37,170
- Wings.
- You know Wings McKay?

362
00:21:37,242 --> 00:21:40,177
<i>Sure. You can never forget</i>
<i>that kind of speed.</i>

363
00:21:40,245 --> 00:21:42,611
[Laughs] Kid's got no second gear,
that's for sure.

364
00:21:42,681 --> 00:21:44,672
It's gonna catch up to him though.

365
00:21:44,750 --> 00:21:47,776
- I don't think anyone can catch him.
- Except the cops.

366
00:21:47,853 --> 00:21:51,482
- <i>[Boy] Hey, Wok, move to second.</i>
- <i>[Boy #2] Come on, Q.</i>

367
00:21:51,557 --> 00:21:55,015
- Just pick up the ball, Q.
- In a minute.

368
00:21:55,094 --> 00:21:57,824
That's Q. Short for I.Q.
He's wicked smart.

369
00:21:57,896 --> 00:21:59,887
Not really that great
an outfielder though.

370
00:21:59,965 --> 00:22:02,991
I'm using the probability calculation
of wind-speed velocity...

371
00:22:03,068 --> 00:22:05,536
versus the angle
of the descent of the ball.

372
00:22:05,604 --> 00:22:09,836
I'm gonna descend upon your head if you
don't pick up that ball and throw it in.

373
00:22:09,908 --> 00:22:13,503
Takes it all apart.
Breaks everything down to a science.

374
00:22:13,579 --> 00:22:16,810
You ever notice how the wind-speed
velocity changes when you speak, Two Ton?

375
00:22:16,882 --> 00:22:18,873
Pick up the ball <i>now.</i>

376
00:22:21,553 --> 00:22:24,886
I guess it paid off. He's only one
of the biggest brain surgeons...

377
00:22:24,957 --> 00:22:27,755
I mean brains in the world.

378
00:22:27,826 --> 00:22:30,317
[Laughs]
You okay, kid?

379
00:22:30,396 --> 00:22:32,990
You might wanna get
out of the sun.

380
00:22:33,065 --> 00:22:37,001
It's not the sun.
I just can't believe what I'm seeing.

381
00:22:37,069 --> 00:22:39,731
That's not good. Here.

382
00:22:39,805 --> 00:22:42,603
You give this card
to your mom, come in...

383
00:22:42,675 --> 00:22:45,075
I'll set you up
with some quality shades.

384
00:22:45,144 --> 00:22:47,738
Speakin' of the shade.
Come on, kid.

385
00:22:47,813 --> 00:22:50,043
Follow me.

386
00:22:50,115 --> 00:22:53,448
What's up with this "kid" crap?

387
00:22:53,519 --> 00:22:56,647
[Benny]
Oh, nice, Timber. Go to second.

388
00:22:59,591 --> 00:23:02,958
- <i>All right, here we go. Another...</i>
- Wings, go to first.

389
00:23:03,028 --> 00:23:06,429
- <i>[Benny] Nice catch.</i>
- That guy taking the mound.

390
00:23:06,498 --> 00:23:09,228
His name's Timber.
That kid can throw some real heat.

391
00:23:09,301 --> 00:23:12,759
- Yeah.
- <i>But he can't pitch at batters, right?</i>

392
00:23:12,838 --> 00:23:16,467
<i>Yeah, left or right. Put anybody in the box,</i>
<i>his arm turns into spaghetti.</i>

393
00:23:18,143 --> 00:23:21,544
- Whoa!
- Sorry.

394
00:23:21,613 --> 00:23:23,808
Okay, that's good.
Just keep throwin' 'em a little lower.

395
00:23:23,882 --> 00:23:25,907
You're doin' good.

396
00:23:25,984 --> 00:23:28,612
Should have worn a batting helmet.

397
00:23:28,687 --> 00:23:31,053
You know a lot
about these kids for a new kid.

398
00:23:31,123 --> 00:23:33,216
- [Chuckles]
- What do you know about Wok and Roll?

399
00:23:33,292 --> 00:23:35,283
It's a little old school.

400
00:23:35,360 --> 00:23:38,329
Lately I've been getting into some
hip-hop, some rap here and there.

401
00:23:38,397 --> 00:23:41,730
What? I'm talking about
Matt "Wok" Wakamoto...

402
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:43,995
and Rolando "Roll" Alvarez.

403
00:23:44,069 --> 00:23:46,970
Of course.
Wok and Roll.

404
00:23:47,039 --> 00:23:49,735
- How could I forget those guys?
- "Forget those guys"?

405
00:23:49,808 --> 00:23:54,108
No, no. I mean, together they play great,
separate they play awful.

406
00:23:54,179 --> 00:23:57,307
If you know so much about these guys,
how come I don't know you?

407
00:23:57,382 --> 00:24:00,317
How come you're not playing?

408
00:24:00,519 --> 00:24:03,147
Okay, guys, bring it in.
Bring it in.

409
00:24:03,222 --> 00:24:06,248
- <i>[Boy] You guys, go. Come on.</i>
- <i>[Boy #2] Go!</i>

410
00:24:06,325 --> 00:24:08,316
Okay, now...

411
00:24:08,393 --> 00:24:12,261
do one of you guys have the guts
to hit off a real major leaguer?

412
00:24:12,331 --> 00:24:15,129
- <i>Oh, no, not me.</i>
- I gotta rest my arm, Benny.

413
00:24:15,200 --> 00:24:17,668
- No, he's your guy.
- I'm the catcher.

414
00:24:17,736 --> 00:24:20,933
Right here, partner.
Right here.

415
00:24:21,006 --> 00:24:24,134
<i>[Boy]</i>
<i>Guys, I gotta see this. Okay, fine.</i>

416
00:24:24,209 --> 00:24:26,939
<i>[Boy #2]</i>
<i>He's gonna get his butt whupped.</i>

417
00:24:27,012 --> 00:24:30,209
- <i>Come on, strike him out, Benny.</i>
- <i>Come on, Benny.</i>

418
00:24:30,282 --> 00:24:34,116
- Strike him out.
- All right.

419
00:24:34,186 --> 00:24:36,882
- What's your name, kid?
- Tommy Santorelli.

420
00:24:36,955 --> 00:24:40,516
And I promise you this.
You're not gonna forget it, Benny.

421
00:24:40,592 --> 00:24:43,390
- Ooh!
- Oh, man.
- <i>Ho, ho.</i>

422
00:24:43,462 --> 00:24:46,829
- Who does this kid think he is, hank Aaron?
- I like your confidence, kid.

423
00:24:46,899 --> 00:24:49,993
- Now let's see what you got.
- This is like deja vu.

424
00:24:50,068 --> 00:24:53,128
- What's like deja vu?
- <i>This</i> is like deja vu.

425
00:24:53,205 --> 00:24:56,868
What's like deja vu?
[Laughs]

426
00:24:56,942 --> 00:24:59,376
Got ya.

427
00:24:59,444 --> 00:25:02,140
I'm just gonna go nice and easy
on ya at first, okay?

428
00:25:02,214 --> 00:25:05,479
You know what, Benny? That's always
been your problem. You're too nice.

429
00:25:05,551 --> 00:25:07,712
- Excuse me?
- You're excused.

430
00:25:07,786 --> 00:25:09,981
[Jeering]

431
00:25:10,055 --> 00:25:13,149
Now bring it.

432
00:25:13,225 --> 00:25:15,250
Okay.

433
00:25:22,100 --> 00:25:24,591
And Santa takes it
to the North Pole.

434
00:25:24,670 --> 00:25:28,436
Nice shot, kid.
All right, now a little more.

435
00:25:37,850 --> 00:25:40,284
You're gonna have to do
better than that, Benny. Come on.

436
00:25:44,923 --> 00:25:47,915
<i>Yeah, I think his swing</i>
<i>might be better than Hank Aaron's.</i>

437
00:25:51,129 --> 00:25:53,029
Yeah.

438
00:25:55,968 --> 00:25:59,369
<i>All right, now, I'm gonna give you</i>
<i>a little more heat, okay?</i>

439
00:25:59,438 --> 00:26:01,872
